<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1068&amp;p=9087#p9087"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">Celius wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Okay, I don't mean to sound retarded. But I am just wondering how you know where the load/init/play addresses in the NSF file are.<br /></div><br />According to the <a href="http://gilgalad.panicus.org/nsf_level/nsfspec.txt" class="postlink">.nsf spec</a>, a .nsf file consists of a 128-byte header segment (which is not loaded into NES CPU address space) followed by several 4096-byte PRG ROM segments (which are).<br /><br />The load, init, and play addresses are located in header at $08, $0A, and $0C respectively and refer to CPU addresses in $8000 through $FFFF. The bytes from $70 through $78 control which PRG ROM segments get loaded into CPU space at load time, but I don't understand how they interact with bankswitching.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Sun Feb 05, 2006 12:14 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
